How customer reviews and ratings work

Customer Reviews, including Product Star Ratings help customers to learn more about the product and decide whether it is the right product for them.

To calculate the overall star rating and percentage breakdown by star, we dont use a simple average. Instead, our system considers things like how recent a review is and if the reviewer bought the item on Amazon. It also analyzed reviews to verify trustworthiness.

R. E. Nelson
5.0 out of 5 stars No pretense of being super-serious!
Reviewed in the United States on February 25, 2024
Verified Purchase
Love this series - a lighthearted approach to futuristic space-based societies, with (in this case) a decent if simplistic and linear plot and lots of action, without the blood, guts and gore of some of the others in the genre. Fortunately, with something of this sort, one has to suspend all belief in reality and critical thinking - like how "The High Evolutionary" (the villain character) seems to have SO much wealth that he could buy a hundred Elon Musks out of pocket change. And it's rewarding to see how Rocket finally comes to grips with his own evolutionary ancestry and identity - something that caused him probems in previous films in the series. We don't watch these for any deep meaning - just a relaxed alternative to the reality of watching the evening news. The cameo appearances by Sly Stone and Nathan Fillion were fun surprises.

Zer0Hour17
3.0 out of 5 stars I still like the characters a lot despite the movie being mediocre.
Reviewed in the United States on October 24, 2023
Verified Purchase
I really, really like the Guardians characters, but I found the movie overall kind of mediocre.

The biggest thing that stuck out to me was the complete tonal whiplash. We go from scenes of horrible animal cruelty and torcher to lol Drax is dumb, back to sad in the course of 5 minutes and it happens over and over. Guardians has always been a mix of comedy and seriousness with some tragedy, but the previous movies were comedies most of the way through but when it was time to get serious they got serious. This one it's back and forth and back and forth.

The biggest mistake of the movie was taking Rocket out of it for 85%. Yes we see him during flashbacks but it's not the same. He's not the rocket we know during them. He is sorely missed in the group dynamic when the Guardians are bumbling around.

I found them repeating the Guardians 1 dynamic of Peter trying to impress Gamora but cold warrior Gamora not having it, until her cold heart melts 80% in again.

Also, and this is not a huge thing I'm deducting points for, I absolutely hate Groots design in this one. They wanted adult Groot again, but it feels like a producer was like "He needs to keep a face closer to baby Groot because we made 10 bajillion dollars on baby Groot merch".

I still love these characters and that carries the movie(and I did laugh some and Rocket's backstory did get me) but the overall plot and progression was just really mediocre and some of the choices drag the overall movie down. Still better than basically all of the slop Marvel has put out post Endgame.
